# What You Just Solved Architecturally

## 1. Hunts as Data

This is the biggest unlock.

Once hunts become pure data:

* creators scale
* modularity scales
* AI-assisted generation becomes possible later
* marketplace compatibility becomes possible
* multiplayer synchronization becomes easier
* cloud save becomes easier
* versioning becomes easier

That single philosophy shift changes everything.

---

# 2. Sponsors as a Layer (Excellent Decision)

You avoided a major trap.

If sponsors became node types:

* the ecosystem becomes brittle
* creators become constrained
* monetization pollutes gameplay architecture

By treating sponsors as overlays/systems:

* any node can become sponsored
* AR hunts remain flexible
* real-world activations stay modular
* branded rewards work universally

That was the right call.

---

# 3. `/player` Instead of `/engine`

This is actually smarter branding and architecture language.

“Engine” implies:

* technical system
* developer-centric mental model

“Player” implies:

* experience layer
* presentation layer
* runtime UX

That distinction matters later when onboarding creators and contributors.

Keeping:

* `/runtime`
* `/player`
* `/creator`

creates a very readable architecture.

---

